INSERT INTO `reply` (`id`, `user_id`, `enquiry_id`, `reply`, `email_flag`, `attachment`, `created_on`, `modified_on`) VALUES
(1, 1, 1, '<p>Under section 79 of the Customs Act, 1969, imported goods require an Import Declaration/Bill of Entry (B/E) to be lodged with Customs so that the goods is cleared legally. Once this Declaration or B/E has been lodged and accepted by Customs, and all duties and taxes paid, goods are released for ?home consumption?. In the case of goods imported by firms with valid bonded warehouse license, Customs allows clearance after assessment of the same under the bonded warehouse facility.&nbsp;</p><p>As Customs uses the automated ASYCUDA World system, Import Declarations or B/Es are required to be submitted in Single Administrative Document (SAD) form. Usually the licensed C&amp; F Agents (Customs brokers) complete the formalities and do the online submission of the Declarations or B/Es to Customs on behalf of the importers.</p>', 0, '', 1463387416, '2016-05-16 08:30:16'),
(2, 1, 2, '<p>Following documents are to be enclosed with the Import Declaration or B/E:</p><ul><li>Invoice;</li><li>Packing List;</li><li>Bill of Lading/Air Way Bill/House Air Way Bill/Truck Receipt/Railway Receipt (as applicable);</li><li>Letter of Credit;</li><li>Letter of Credit Authorization;</li><li>VAT/BIN certificate;</li><li>Country of Origin certificate;</li><li>Insurance cover note:&nbsp;</li><li>Certificate/documents (from other government agencies (OGAs), to support importability; or to claim duty benefits? where necessary); and</li><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Other documents (as required from time to time by the Government/the National Board of Revenue/other government agencies).</span></li></ul>', 0, '', 1463387460, '2016-05-16 08:31:00'),
(3, 1, 3, '<p>The procedures for import against direct payment abroad are laid down in paragraph 8, sub-paragraph 7 of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018. Only Bangladeshi nationals living abroad may send any importable item irrespective of value ceiling against direct payment abroad in the name of any Bangladeshi living in Bangladesh. The name and address of the consignee must be mentioned in the import documents. In such cases ?&nbsp;</p><p>(a) No permission or import permit from the import Control Authority will be necessary;</p><p>(b) A certificate from the Bangladesh Embassy in that country as an earner of foreign exchange has to be submitted. Sender?s passport number, occupation, annual income, period of stay abroad etc. must be mentioned in that certificate; and</p><p>(c) The payment receipt of the goods must be certified by the Embassy.</p><p>Note: For more information, please contact Ministry of Commerce.</p>', 0, '', 1463387628, '2016-05-16 08:33:48'),
(4, 1, 4, '<p>Various categories of items require testing, in some cases mandatory, before their Customs clearance. For example-</p><ul><li>Food products: As per conditions under Paragraph 16(5) of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018, samples from consignments of milk, milk food, milk products, fish products, edible oil and other food items will have to be tested by the Bangladesh Atomic Energy Commission to check the radiation level.</li><ul><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">However, under paragraph 16(16) of the Import Policy Order, this provision is not applicable in case of imports of rice, wheat, other food grains, and food products from SAARC, South-East Asia and Asia-Pacific Ocean countries.</span></li></ul><li>RBD Palm Stearin: As per conditions under Paragraph 16(11) of the Import Policy Order, tests for determination of purity of RBD Palm Stearin will be carried out by the BSTI/BCSIR.&nbsp;</li><li>Raw cotton: As per conditions under paragraph 26(60) of the Import Policy Order, fumigation is mandatory in case of import of American cotton (i.e., raw cotton) produced and packed in the western hemisphere.</li><li>Standards issues: As per conditions under paragraph 26(28) of the Import Policy Order, 55 categories of products are subject standards control system as per Bangladesh Standard (BDS) specified by BSTI. &nbsp;Note: For details on conditions related to conforming to BDS standard and customs clearance of these 55 categories of procedures, please consult the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018 (paragraph 26(28)).</li></ul><p>Note: For more information on testing requirements, please consult Import Policy Order, 2015-2018 or contact Ministry of Commerce.</p>', 0, '', 1463387739, '2016-05-16 08:35:39'),
(5, 1, 5, '<p>As per the conditions under Paragraph 16(5) of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018, samples from consignments of milk, milk food, milk products, fish products, edible oil and other food items will have to be tested by the Bangladesh Atomic Energy Commission to check the radiation level. However, under paragraph 16(16) of the same order, this provision is not applicable in case of imports of rice, wheat, other food grains, and food products from SAARC, South-East Asia and Asia-Pacific Ocean countries.</p><p>Note: For more information, please contact Ministry of Commerce.</p>', 0, '', 1463387799, '2016-05-16 08:36:39'),
(6, 1, 6, '<p>No.</p><p>As per the conditions under Paragraph 16(13) of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018, in the case of import of spices and medicine, cigarette, cigarette paper, pipe tobacco, whiskey, beer and other alcoholic beverages, concentrated essence, radioactivity test is &nbsp;not be necessary.</p><p>Note: For more information, please contact Ministry of Commerce.</p>', 0, '', 1463387821, '2016-05-16 08:37:01'),
(7, 1, 7, '<p>Yes.&nbsp;</p><p>An importer can clear his own imported consignment. Rule 10 of the Customs Agents (Licensing) Rules, 2009 of the NBR permits the importers to use the self-clearance facility in order to clear goods imported by him.&nbsp;</p><p>However, in practice, most importers and exporters refrain from availing this facility, and instead uses the services of a clearing and forwarding agent or Customs broker for this purpose.&nbsp;</p>', 0, '', 1463387840, '2016-05-16 08:37:20'),
(8, 1, 8, '<p>These are the different CPCs (Customs Procedure Codes) used for Customs assessment and clearance under the automated ASYCUDA World system.&nbsp;</p><p>IM 4 CPC is used for dutiable goods on which customs duties and taxes are payable.&nbsp;</p><p>IM 7 CPC is used for goods imported under the warehousing facility. IM 7 covers those declarations that relate to goods which are assessed and cleared under the bonded warehousing facility without payment of duty.&nbsp;</p>', 0, '', 1463387857, '2016-05-16 08:37:37'),
(9, 1, 9, '<p>In the case of general import of animals, plants and plant products, quarantine conditions are applicable under paragraph 26(41) of Import Policy Order, 2015-2018. Again, imports and exports of plant and plant products will be subject to Plant Quarantine Act, 2011.</p><p>Note: For more details on these issues, please consult Import Policy Order, 2015-2018 or contact the Plant Quarantine Department under Ministry of Agriculture.</p>', 0, '', 1463387873, '2016-05-16 08:37:53'),
(10, 1, 10, '<p>In the case of import of live animals, quarantine conditions are applicable under paragraph 26(41) of Import Policy Order, 2015-2018.</p><p>Again, as per paragraph 26(44) of the Import Policy Order, one day old chicks (HS Heading 01.05) are importable provided the importer fulfils the following conditions:</p><p>(a)&nbsp;Submit to Customs a certificate issued by the authorized officer of Livestock Department of the exporting country stating that the importable chicks are free from contagious disease;&nbsp;</p><p>(b)&nbsp;Submit to Customs a certificate issued by the World Organization of Animal Health stating that the exporting country is free from Avian Influenza</p><p>(c)&nbsp;Submit to the Bank, prior to opening of L/C, a certificate from the Directorate of Livestock that he has either a hatchery or a breeder farm.</p><p>Note: For more details on these issues, please consult Import Policy Order, 2015-2018 or contact the Ministry of Fisheries and Livestock.&nbsp;</p>', 0, '', 1463387901, '2016-05-16 08:38:21'),
(11, 1, 11, '<p>The conditions for import of food items as relief goods by the government are set under SRO No. 61-Law/92/1444/Cus, dated 17 March, 1992. &nbsp;A certificate by an officer not below the rank of Deputy Secretary of the concerned government ministry must be issued in favor of the concerned Commissioner of Customs that the goods are received as relief materials for distribution free of cost among the destitute/poor people/organizations, and that the goods will not be otherwise sold or used in any other way.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">The government department importing the goods must provide an undertaking addressing the concerned Commissioner of Customs that it will remain liable to pay the assessable duties, VAT and supplementary duties if the goods received are disposed of in any manner other than free distribution.</span></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Apart from that, the goods have to be found suitable for human consumption at the lab test conducted by the Ministry of Food. However, the general certificate to the effect that the items are fit for human consumption must be enclosed with the Bill of Lading, according to &nbsp;paragraph 16(3)(e) of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018.</span></p>', 0, '', 1463387930, '2016-05-16 08:38:50'),
(12, 1, 12, '<p>Before opening the Letter of Credit in order to import Pesticides and Insecticides, banks will have to ensure that the importers of such goods have valid product registration certificate (as per the Pesticides Rules, 1985 framed under ?The Pesticides Ordinance, 1971?) &nbsp;from the Department of Agricultural Extension and an import license.&nbsp;</p><p>Again, Bangladesh Bank has recently advised scheduled banks to exercise caution in this matter by ensuring that the importer has necessary product registration certificate and import license from the Directorate of Agriculture Extension. [Reference: Bangladesh Bank FEPD Circular no. FEPD (Amdani Niti)/115/2015-15 date- 10 Aug 2015]</p>', 0, '', 1463387945, '2016-05-16 08:39:05'),
(13, 1, 13, '<p>As per the provisions of Paragraph 5(6) of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018, a ?country of origin? certificate issued by the concerned Government agency, approved authority or organization of the exporting country must be submitted, along with import documents to the Customs Authority at the time of release of goods.&nbsp;</p><p>However, this country of origin certificate is not required in the case of imports of coal, imports by export-oriented garments industries, and imports of raw materials by industries.&nbsp;</p><p>Note: For more information, please contact the Ministry of Commerce.</p>', 0, '', 1463387959, '2016-05-16 08:39:19'),
(14, 1, 14, '<p>For the purpose of determining the assessable value of a imported consignment at a Customs airport, an amount equal to 15% of the freight published by International Air Transport Agency (IATA) will be taken as freight for carrying the consignment at that airport. [Reference: SRO 129-Law-99/1792/Cus, dated 10 June 1999]<br></p>', 0, '', 1463387973, '2016-05-16 08:39:33'),
(15, 1, 15, '<p>As per conditions under paragraph 26(60) of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018, fumigation is mandatory in case of import of American cotton that means raw cotton produced and packed in western hemisphere. Such fumigation has to be done by the Quarantine officials.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Again, as per paragraph 5(6)(d) of the Import Policy Order, in case of import of cotton it is not necessary &nbsp;to mention ?country of origin? on each bale, provided that the ?country of origin? &nbsp;is mentioned in the phyto-sanitary certificate.</span></p><p>Note: For more information, please contact the Ministry of Commerce.</p>', 0, '', 1463387996, '2016-05-16 08:39:56'),
(16, 1, 16, '<p>Documents needed or Formalities to be completed in the case of import of all kinds of milk food products including baby food with fat contents covered under H.S. Heading 04.02 or H.S Heading 19.01 and all HS Codes classifiable thereunder are elaborated in Paragraph 16(17) of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018. Some of the major provisions are mentioned below:</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">(a)&nbsp;</span><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">The words: ?????? ????? ?????? ??? ? (There is no alternative to breastfeeding) shall be printed clearly in relatively larger fonts in Bangla in a visible space on each tin or airtight package or Bag in&nbsp;</span><br></p><p>Box of baby food with cream;</p><p>(b)&nbsp;Composition and percentages of different ingredients shall be printed in Bangla on the tin containers or airtight packages or Bag in Boxes of milk food; and</p><p>(c)&nbsp;The date of manufacture and the date of expiry (for human consumption) of milk food shall be embossed or computer printed in permanent ink either in Bangla or in English on each airtight package with tin container or bag in box.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Moreover, the additional documents needed or the additional formalities to be completed in the case of import of non-fat powdered milk are elaborated in Paragraph 16(18) of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018.&nbsp;</span></p><p>Note: For more information, please contact the Ministry of Commerce.</p>', 0, '', 1463388031, '2016-05-16 08:40:31'),
(17, 1, 17, '<p>In order to open a Letter of Credit (L/C) to import plant and plant products, a valid import permit has to be obtained beforehand from the Quarantine wing of the Departmental of Agricultural Extension (DAE). According to the Destructive Insects and Pests Rules, 1966, it is a mandatory requirement to obtain an import permit from the DAE prior to such importation (i.e. before opening an L/C).&nbsp;</p><p>Note: For more information, please contact the Ministry of Agriculture.</p>', 0, '', 1463388047, '2016-05-16 08:40:47'),
(18, 1, 18, '<p>As Customs uses the automated ASYCUDA World system, as in the case of Import Declaration or Bill of Entry, the Export Declaration or Bill of Export also requires to be submitted in Single Administrative Document (SAD) form. Following documents are to be enclosed with the Export Declaration or Bill of Export:</p><ul><li>Valid export LC/ Export Contract or Order or Guarantee/ Sales Contract for BBLC;</li><li>Invoice;</li><li>Packing List;</li><li>EXP Form;</li><li>Certificate of Origin (C/O);</li><li>Utilization Declaration or Utilization Permission (in case of export import under special bonded warehousing);&nbsp;</li><li>Export Registration Certificate issued by CCI&amp;E;</li><li>VAT/BIN certificate; and</li><li>Other necessary documents (as required from time to time by the Government/the National Board of Revenue/other government agencies).</li></ul>', 0, '', 1463388081, '2016-05-16 08:41:21'),
(19, 1, 19, '<p>As per the Guidelines for Foreign Exchange Transaction, exports can be made without LC if there is a Sales Contract. In that case, the size, quantity and quality of the product has to conform to the conditions of the Sales Contract. Again, as per paragraph 4 under Chapter 8 of the said Guidelines, all exports to which the requirement of declaration applies must be declare don the EXP Form.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Note: For more information, please contact Bangladesh Bank.</span></p>', 0, '', 1463388243, '2016-05-16 08:44:03'),
(20, 1, 20, '<p>Following documents are required to be submitted with the Bill of Export to export vegetables to the EU market:</p><ol><li>Export Letter of Credit/export contract or order&nbsp;</li><li>Invoice</li><li>Packing List</li><li>EXP form</li><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Certificate of Origin (C/O)</span></li><li>Phytosanitary certificate (PC) issued by the Department of Agricultural Extension.&nbsp;</li></ol><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Without this Phyto-sanitary Certificate, exports of vegetables/fruit will not be allowed to markets in the European countries.&nbsp;</span></p>', 0, '', 1463388284, '2016-05-16 08:44:44'),
(21, 1, 21, '<p>Yes.</p><p>The provision regarding this issue is delineated under the NBR office order no. 7(12)Cus-1/94/502, dated 23 August 2005.</p><p>According to this provision, when machinery/spare parts are re-imported after conducting repair works abroad, duty will have to be paid.</p>', 0, '', 1463388357, '2016-05-16 08:45:57'),
(22, 1, 22, '<p>In the case of sending a machinery/parts overseas for repair, and re-importing it after repair, the importer shall have to require an <b>Export-cum-Import permit, issued by the Office of the CCI&amp;E.</b></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">In the case of re-importation of the machinery/parts, Customs will need to conduct physical inspection/examination to ensure that the imported machinery/parts is the same that were exported earlier. &nbsp;Duties will be assessed and collected on the value as determined below:</span></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\"><b>C&amp;F Price = Repair cost + Inward freight charge</b></span></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">This C &amp; F price will be used as the assessable value for Customs purposes. The duty rate to be applied shall be the duty rate applicable to the concerned machinery/parts.</span></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">If machinery/parts re-imported are not the same machinery/parts that were exported for the purpose of repairing, the aforesaid method will not be applicable. For importation of replacement parts/machinery, duties and taxes will be realizable as a fresh import.</span></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">(Reference: Office Order NBR nothi no. 7(12)-Cus-1/94/502. Date- 23/08/2005)</span></p>', 0, '', 1463388429, '2016-05-16 08:47:09'),
(23, 1, 23, '<p>Carnet de passage is an internationally recognized Customs document. The Carnet de Passage system allows travelers/ tourists to move through countries driving their own vehicles. Such vehicles are allowed to enter the traveling country on temporary importation facilities without payment of any duty and taxes.&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Travelers / tourists will have to carry a Carnet issued by the competent authority from their home country. This facility has been enabled under the 1954 UN Convention titled ?Customs Convention on the Temporary Importation of Private Road Vehicles?. Bangladesh has not been a signatory to the said convention.</span></p>', 0, '', 1463388466, '2016-05-16 08:47:46'),
(24, 1, 24, '<p>As per the 1954 UN Convention titled ?Customs Convention on the Temporary Importation of Private Road Vehicles?, a Carnet is valid for 12 months from the date of issue. But Bangladesh has not been a signatory to the said convention.<br></p>', 0, '', 1463388558, '2016-05-16 08:49:18'),
(25, 1, 25, '<p>An outgoing passenger can take a maximum amount of Tk. 5000 out of Bangladesh without a declaration. An incoming passenger can bring Tk. 5000 into Bangladesh without a declaration.<br></p>', 0, '', 1463388581, '2016-05-16 08:49:41'),
(26, 1, 26, '<p>All types of dealings in foreign exchange are guided by The Foreign Exchange Regulation Act 1947, which is administered by Bangladesh Bank.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">An adult passenger can take out up to US$ 12,000 during a calendar year for global private travel. Out of the US$ 12,000, up to US$ 5,000 or equivalent for travel to SAARC member countries and Myanmar, and up to US$ 7,000 or equivalent for travel to other countries.</span></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">For minors (below 12 years in age) the applicable quota will be half the amount admissible for adults. However, foreign exchange (take out from Bangladesh) in the form of cash must not exceed US$ 5,000 per person per trip. (Ref. FE Circular No. 17 of 06/04/2014 and FE Circular No. 02 of 11/02/2015)</span></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">For official or semi-official visits abroad by the officials of Government/Autonomous/Semi-autonomous institutions etc., ADs may release foreign exchange as per entitlements fixed by the Ministry of Finance/respective competent authority from time to time. In such cases, the applicant for foreign exchange shall be required to submit the Competent Authority\'s Order/Notification /Circular authorizing the travel abroad. (Ref. Para 3, Chapter 12 of GFET, Guidelines for Foreign Exchange Transactions)</span></p>', 0, '', 1463388619, '2016-05-16 08:50:19'),
(27, 1, 27, '<p>There are fixed rate of duties and taxes on Television sets of\r\n	different sizes/descriptions. The rates are as below:</p>\r\n<table class=\"table table-bordered\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width: 200px;\">Plasma, LCD, TFT, LED Television</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width: 200px;\">Duties Tk. (total)</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>22?-29?</td>\r\n			<td>Tk. 10,000</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>30?-36?</td>\r\n			<td>15,000</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>37?- 42?</td>\r\n			<td>20,000</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>43?-46?</td>\r\n			<td>30,000</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>47?-52?</td>\r\n			<td>50,000</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>53? and above</td>\r\n			<td>70,000</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>', 0, '', 1463389077, '2016-05-16 08:57:57'),
(28, 1, 28, '<p>Usually one video camera can be brought in duty free as a baggage item by any passenger. But, HD Cam, DV Cam, BETA Cam and camera used for professional purpose brought in by a passenger are not entitled to receive such facility.<br></p><hr /><p class=\"text-right small\">Additional Resources: <a href=\"http://bangladeshcustoms.gov.bd/beta/download/Passenger_Baggage_Declaration_Form.pdf\" target=\"_new\">Passenger Baggage Declaration Form</a>', 0, '', 1463389329, '2016-05-16 09:02:09'),
(29, 1, 29, '<p>Yes.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Provided that he satisfies the conditions under the Tourists Baggage (Import) Rules, 1981, a tourist may import, free of duty, one non-professional video camera.</span></p>', 0, '', 1463389356, '2016-05-16 09:02:36'),
(30, 1, 30, '<p>According to Rule 3(9) of Passenger (Non-tourist) Baggage (Import) Rules, 2012 (NBR SRO no. 172-Law/2012/2400/Cus, dated 07/06/2012), a passenger can bring gold ornaments weighing not more than 100 gram or silver ornaments weighing not more than 200 grams (one item not more than 12 pieces) without payment of any duty and taxes.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Again, according to Rule 2(10) of the same Rules, a passenger can bring gold bar or gold bullion weighing not more than 200 gram, or silver bar or silver bullion weighing not more than 200 grams on payment of all duty and taxes.</span></p>', 0, '', 1463389388, '2016-05-16 09:03:08'),
(31, 22, 31, '<p>In the case of passengers carrying any plant or soil, including fruits (mango, orange, papaya, etc.), vegetables, seeds, orchids, nursery stock or cut flowers, etc., they must declare all such products to the airport quarantine officers upon arrival at the Customs Hall, where they must be inspected.&nbsp;<br></p>', 0, '', 1463389406, '2016-05-16 09:03:26'),
(32, 1, 32, '<p>Computers are known as automatic data processing machines, and are classifiable under HS Heading 84.71. General import of such computers are not duty free. But a passenger is entitled duty free benefits for computers.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">For example, a passenger can bring along with him a desktop/laptop computer (with UPS), a computer scanner and a computer printer without paying any duty. This facility is available under the Passenger (Non-tourist) Baggage (Import) Rules, 2011.&nbsp;</span></p>', 0, '', 1463389434, '2016-05-16 09:03:54'),
(33, 1, 33, '<p>Motor parts are not categorized by the NBR as personal effects. Therefore, if any passenger brings motor parts along with his baggage of personal effects, he will not be able to claim duty free benefits for these motor parts. Customs may even ask for an import permit to clear such non baggage items before clearance if it is considered to be of commercial quantity.<br></p>', 0, '', 1463389447, '2016-05-16 09:04:07'),
(34, 1, 34, '<p>A passenger who is a Bangladeshi citizen is not allowed to bring liqueurs (e. g. spirit, beer etc.) with him.&nbsp;</p><p>However, passengers holding foreign passports are allowed to import liqueurs. Under the Passenger (Non-tourist) Baggage (Import) Rules, 2011, a foreign passport holder can along bring duty two bottles or one liter of alcohols or liqueurs (e. g. spirit or beer etc.).</p>', 0, '', 1463389477, '2016-05-16 09:04:37'),
(35, 1, 35, '<p>Even if a passenger brings a Spot light as a baggage item, he will have to pay @Tk. 300/- duty for each point of the Spot light.<br></p>', 0, '', 1463389505, '2016-05-16 09:05:05'),
(36, 1, 36, '<p>According to Rule 10 of the Passenger (Non-Tourists) Baggage (Import) Rules, 2012, goods imported as baggage in excess of goods listed in Schedule 2 and Schedule 3 of the Rules or goods of other description shall be considered commercial baggage. Such ?commercial quantity baggage? shall be eligible for clearance only on production of Import Permit from the CCI&amp;E and on payment of applicable duties and taxes including penalty (if any).<br></p>', 0, '', 1463389574, '2016-05-16 09:06:14'),
(37, 1, 37, '<p>The Transfer of Residence facility is elaborated in Transfer of Residence Baggage (Import) Rules, 2000. A passenger who has decided to reside in Bangladesh after a continuous stay abroad for two (2) years or more is entitled to enjoy facility under the Transfer of Residence Baggage (Import) Rules, 2000.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Under this baggage rule, depreciation allowance will be given for specified items within the value limit laid down in the Rule. The passenger is also entitled to duty free clearance of used and old clothes, books, bedding and professional equipment (up to 1000 dollars of value).&nbsp;</span></p>', 0, '', 1463389591, '2016-05-16 09:06:31'),
(38, 1, 38, '<p>Yes.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">An expatriate Bangladeshi national who is transferring his residence to Bangladesh after staying for at least two years in another country is allowed to import his/her used motor car without an Import Permit/Clearance Permit from the CCI&amp;E, as per the provisions under the Transfer of Residence Baggage (Import) Rules, 2000. However, such import will have to be subject to fulfillment of other conditions under the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018 (Part A under Annexure 1) concerning motor cars.</span></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">The person will not be entitled to receive the depreciated value benefit as offered under the Transfer of Residence Baggage (Import) Rules. Valuation for such motor car will be determined as per the depreciated value rules applicable for the general/commercial imports of old/used/reconditioned motor cars.&nbsp;</span></p>', 0, '', 1463389646, '2016-05-16 09:07:26'),
(39, 1, 39, '<p>The formalities required to clear accompanied baggage are laid down in the Passenger (Non-Tourist) Baggage (Import) Rules, 2012. The concerned passenger has to declare unaccompanied baggage (in brief) in the Form specified in Schedule 1 in the Passenger (Non-Tourist) Baggage (Import) Rules, 2012 and before leaving the Customs Hall get it signed by the Revenue officer posted at airport.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Later, the passenger will need to go to the Air Freight Unit of the concerned Custom House and submit a manual bill of entry along with the aforesaid Form and other documents (AWB, passport etc.). Then he will be able to clear the goods without paying any duty and taxes provided the items brought satisfy the conditions under the (Non-Tourist) Baggage (Import) Rules, 2012.</span></p>', 0, '', 1463389682, '2016-05-16 09:08:02'),
(40, 1, 40, '<p>Cash incentives offered to various sectors during the fiscal year 2015-2016 are elaborated in the Bangladesh Bank F.E. Circular 08, July 13, 2015. Cash incentives will cover over 150 goods and products under 14 categories, most of which are from the farm sector. Under the cash incentive programme, small and medium garment factories will get additional 5.0 per cent subsidy when 2.0 per cent will be provided for new products and new market expansion (except USA/Canada/EU).</p> \n<p>Potato, halal meat and agro-products will get the highest 20.0 per cent cash subsidy. Among the other sectors, frozen shrimp and jute yarn will get 7.5 per cent and ship export will get 5.0 per cent cash subsidy. Details of cash incentives applicable in FY 2015-16 are provided below:</p>\n<table class=\"table table-bordered\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>1</td>\n			<td>Export oriented local textiles industry that do not enjoy Customs bond or duty-drawback facility</td>\n			<td>4%</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>2</td>\n		    <td>Alternative cash subsidy instead of Customs bond and duty-drawback facilities for small and medium sized export-oriented textiles sector</td>\n		    <td>4%</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>3</td>\n		    <td>Cash incentives for exporting new products and exploring new markets (textile sector) outside USA, Canada and EU</td>\n		    <td>3%</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>4</td>\n		    <td>Cash incentive for the export of  products, which are made of elephant grass (hogla), paddy straw (khor) and sugarcane bark (akher chobra),</td>\n		    <td>at the rate between 15%  and 20%</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>5</td>\n		    <td>Export subsidy for Agri products (vegetables/fruits) and Agro processed items</td>\n		    <td>20%</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>6</td>\n		    <td>Cash incentives for export of bone dust</td>\n		    <td>5%</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>7</td>\n		    <td>Incentive for export of products of light engineering sector</td>\n		    <td>15%</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>8</td>\n		    <td>For export of 100% halal meat (export subsidy)</td>\n		    <td>20%</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>9</td>\n		    <td colspan=\"2\">\n		      <table width=\"100%\" class=\"table table-bordered\">\n		          <tr>\n		              <td>For exports of frozen shrimp, if the ice cover is</td>\n		              <td></td>\n		          </tr>\n		          <tr>\n		              <td>up to 20%</td>\n		              <td>10%</td>\n		          </tr>\n		          <tr>\n		              <td>above 20% to 30%</td>\n		              <td>9%</td>\n		          </tr>\n		          <tr>\n		              <td>above 30% to 40%</td>\n		              <td>8%</td>\n		          </tr>\n		          <tr>\n		              <td>above 40%</td>\n		              <td>7%</td>\n		          </tr>\n		          <tr>\n		              <td>For other frozen fish, if the ice cover is:</td>\n		              <td></td>\n		          </tr>\n		          <tr>\n		              <td>up to 20%</td>\n		              <td>5%</td>\n		          </tr>\n		          <tr>\n		              <td>above 20% to 30%</td>\n		              <td>4%</td>\n		          </tr>\n		          <tr>\n		              <td>above 30% to 40%</td>\n		              <td>3%</td>\n		          </tr>\n		          <tr>\n		              <td>above 40%</td>\n		              <td>2%</td>\n		          </tr>\n		      </table>\n		    </td>\n		    \n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>10</td>\n		    <td>Cash incentives for export of  leather products</td>\n		    <td></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>11</td>\n		    <td>Export subsidy against export of ships</td>\n		    <td></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>12</td>\n		    <td>Cash incentives for export of potato</td>\n		    <td></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>13</td>\n		    <td>Export subsidy for export of PET bottle-for potato flakes</td>\n		    <td></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>14</td>\n		    <td>Cash incentives for export of jute products:</td>\n		    <td>\n		    	<ul>\n				<li>Diversified Jute goods: 10%</li> \n				<li>Jute products (Hesian, sacking and CBC): 7.5%</li>\n				<li>Jute yarn: 5%</li> \n				</ul>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>	\n<p>(Source: Bangladesh Bank, F.E. Circular 08, July 13, 2015)</p>\n<p>However, these export incentives/subsidies may vary from year to year. It is advisable to visit Bangladesh Bank website (https://www.bb.org.bd) for any changes or updates in cash incentive rates and/or items.</p>', 0, '', 1463391051, '2016-05-16 09:30:51'),
