ther extend the bonding period for 3 months<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n  </td>\r\n </tr>\r\n <tr style=\"mso-yfti-irow:6;mso-yfti-lastrow:yes\">\r\n  <td width=\"230\" valign=\"top\" style=\"width:229.8pt;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;\r\n  border-top:none;mso-border-top-alt:solid windowtext .5pt;mso-border-alt:solid windowtext .5pt;\r\n  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt\">\r\n  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-font-family:\r\n  Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\r\n  mso-bidi-font-weight:bold\">Ship Builders Bond<span style=\"mso-spacerun:yes\">&nbsp;\r\n  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n  </td>\r\n  <td width=\"229\" valign=\"top\" style=\"width:228.7pt;border-top:none;border-left:\r\n  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;\r\n  mso-border-top-alt:solid windowtext .5pt;mso-border-left-alt:solid windowtext .5pt;\r\n  mso-border-alt:solid windowtext .5pt;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt\">\r\n  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-font-family:\r\n  Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\r\n  mso-bidi-font-weight:bold\">48 Months; <o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n  <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-font-family:\r\n  Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\r\n  mso-bidi-font-weight:bold\">Bonding period is extendable. <o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n  </td>\r\n </tr>\r\n</tbody></table><p>Note: Commissioner reserves the power to extend the bonding period for a maximum of 6 months in the case of special bonded warehouse, direct exporters, and deemed exporters. In other cases, Commissioner may extend the bonding period for 3 months and the NBR may then extend the bonding period for a further period of 3 months.<br></p>', 0, '', 1463391896, '2016-05-16 09:44:56');
INSERT INTO `reply` (`id`, `user_id`, `enquiry_id`, `reply`, `email_flag`, `attachment`, `created_on`, `modified_on`) VALUES
(50, 1, 50, '<p>The following formalities are to be observed in order to get permission for extension of bonding period for raw materials:&nbsp;</p><ol><li>An application for extension of bonding period for raw materials has to be submitted to the respective Customs Bond Commissionerate.</li><li>A recommendation letter on the quality of raw materials from the concerned association to be submitted along with the application.</li><li>After receiving that recommendation, the concerned bond officer will physically inspect the stock and quality of the raw-materials, and submit his report in a prescribe format. If the report is OK, i.e. if the raw materials are found accurate in correct quantity and good quality respectively, the extension order would be issued.</li></ol>', 0, '', 1463391959, '2016-05-16 09:45:59'),
(51, 1, 51, '<p>This has been elaborated in the Rule 12 of the Bonded Warehouse Licensing Rules, 2008 (SRO no. 181-Law/2008/2209/Cus, dated 26/06/2008). The amount of general bond to be executed by different types of bonded warehouses for duty free imports, warehousing and use of inputs/raw materials and subsequent exports are as follows:</p><table class=\"table table-bordered\"><tbody><tr><td>Sl. No.<br></td><td>Type of Bonded Warehouse<br></td><td>Amount of general bond<br></td></tr><tr><td>1</td><td>For deemed exporters&nbsp;<br></td><td>Tk. 1 crore (10,000,000)<br></td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>For licensees having both deemed and direct exports<br></td><td>Tk. 2 crore (20,000,000)<br></td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>For direct exporters&nbsp;<br></td><td>Tk. 3 crore (30,000,000)<br></td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>For diplomatic, duty free and duty paid warehouses&nbsp;<br></td><td>Tk. 3 crore (30,000,000)<br></td></tr></tbody></table><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">The Bonded warehouse licensing authority may increase the amount of General Bond considering the volume of import and export activities by the bonder.</span><br></p>', 0, '', 1463392092, '2016-05-16 09:48:12'),
(52, 1, 52, '<p>Following documents are needed to be submitted along with the application for a Utilization Permission (UP) -</p><ul><li>Back to Back Letter of Credit/Sales Contract/Import Permit;</li><li>Pro forma Invoice;</li><li>Utilization Declaration; and</li><li>Master LC.</li></ul>', 0, '', 1463392114, '2016-05-16 09:48:34'),
(53, 1, 53, '<p>Yes.</p><p>If all the conditions for getting a bond license are met, bonded warehouse license may be issued in favour of different organizations located in the same building. &nbsp;</p><p>[Reference NBR letter no 3(2): Shulka: Raptani o bond/2001/1326, dated 10/10/2001 (decision taken in a meeting between NBR and BGMEA)]</p>', 0, '', 1463392130, '2016-05-16 09:48:50'),
(54, 1, 54, '<p>All bonded warehouses are subject to a mandatory audit each year.<br></p>', 0, '', 1463392141, '2016-05-16 09:49:01'),
(55, 1, 55, '<p>The procedure has been elaborated by the NBR memo no. 1(3): Shukla-Roptani O Bond/97, dated 12/06/1997. &nbsp;Fabrics necessary for manufacturing samples of readymade garments/clothes may be imported under the bonded warehouse facility through passbooks. The amount of fabrics of different types that will be allowed to import under bond are:</p><table class=\"table table-bordered\"><tbody><tr><td>Samples<br></td><td>Maximum amount<br></td></tr><tr><td>Woven fabrics<br></td><td>Not more than 1% of the quantity of fabrics approved under the Utilization Declaration. However, for a single export order, it must not be more than 200 Yards.<br></td></tr><tr><td>Wool/Acrylic/Knitwear fabrics<br></td><td>Not more than 1.5% of the quantity of fabrics approved under the Utilization Declaration. However, for a single export order, it must not be more than 200 Pounds.<br></td></tr><tr><td>Yarn<br></td><td>Not more than 1.5% of the quantity of fabrics approved under the Utilization Declaration. However, for a single export order, it must not be more than 200 Pounds.</td></tr></tbody></table>', 0, '', 1463392221, '2016-05-16 09:50:21'),
(56, 1, 56, '<p>Vehicles (car), pickup, jeep and microbus imported by firms located in export processing zones are exempted from Customs duty, Value Added Tax, &nbsp;and Supplementary Duty (where applicable) subject to fulfilment of conditions laid down in SRO 151-Act/99/1787/Customs and VAT date 10/06/1999.&nbsp;</p><p>Some of the conditions include:</p><ol><li>The firm importing the vehicles must have 100% foreign capital investment;&nbsp;</li><li>In the case of Joint Venture, foreign investment in terms of capital of the firm must be more than 50%;</li><li>If the amount of foreign capital is not more than 50%, a certificate from the BEPZA to the effect that at least 500 Bangladeshi citizens have been employed or will be employed in the firm will have to be submitted to the Customs Authority;</li><li>Vehicles (car), pickup, jeep and microbus imported under this order will not be transferred through sale or any other arrangement within five years from the date of clearance of the same; and</li><li>Vehicles (car), pickup, jeep and microbus imported will not be used for purposes other than for production or related activities of the firm or for any other commercial purpose.</li></ol>', 0, '', 1463392286, '2016-05-16 09:51:26'),
(57, 1, 57, '<p>Goods may be taken out of the Export Processing Zones to the Domestic Tariff Area (DTA) on fulfilment of conditions laid down in the NBR Standing Order no. 18/2009/Shulka, date- 31.08.2009 and conditions to be imposed by orders to be issued from time to time.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Such transfer to the DTA from the EPZs after fulfilment of prescribed requirements is considered as import of goods from out of Bangladesh.&nbsp;</span></p><p>As per the provisions of SRO no. 545-Law/84/889/Cus, dated 10/12/1984., goods removed for home consumption will be subject to applicable duties and taxes. The value and rate of duties and other taxes applicable to such goods will be determined in accordance with the provisions of the Act and rules made thereunder.</p>', 0, '', 1463392310, '2016-05-16 09:51:50'),
(58, 1, 58, '<p>Following documents are required to be submitted to Customs to export (foreign or local) from the EPZ area:</p><ol><li>Bill of Export</li><li>Export Permit from BEPZA</li><li>Letter of Credit</li><li>Letter of Credit of Authorization</li><li>Invoice</li><li>Packing List</li><li>Pass Book</li><li>EXP</li><li>Delivery Challan</li><li>Utilization Declaration (if applicable)</li><li>Other documents, if applicable.</li></ol>', 0, '', 1463392345, '2016-05-16 09:52:25'),
(59, 1, 59, '<p>Yes.</p><p>The relevant divisional officer of Customs may allow a limited number of samples to be taken out from the EPZ to domestic tariff areas (DTAs) on special grounds subject to fulfilment of the provisions under Section 94 (1) (E) of the Customs Act, 1969. These samples will be adjusted against the final export.</p>', 0, '', 1463392359, '2016-05-16 09:52:39'),
(60, 1, 60, '<p>On a matter suitable for Alternate Dispute Resolution (ADR) mechanism, but is pending before any court in Bangladesh, a concerned importer/ exporter/PSI Agency may lodge an application to the concerned Commissioner of Customs to settle the matter through ADR. In this case, the applicant will have to obtain permission from the concerned court, and after obtaining such permission from the said court, and upon granting of such permission by the court the matter shall remain stayed during the period of ADR process:</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">However, according to Section 192E of the Customs Act, 1969, this is conditional upon the court?s disposing of any such writ petition with directions to any of the above authorities to settle the matter through ADR. Then the authority will settle the case accordingly, if not otherwise barred by law.</span></p>', 0, '', 1464232993, '2016-05-26 03:23:13'),
(61, 1, 61, '<p>Drawback is the refund of duties and taxes paid on inputs/raw materials used for the manufacture of exported goods and services. The term ?Drawback? is used exclusively for refund of duties and taxes against export. Under the provisions of sub-section (1) of section 13 of The Value Added Tax Act, 1991 read with section 37 of The Customs Act, 1969 all duties and taxes paid on inputs/raw materials used for the manufacture of exported goods or services shall be refunded except income tax paid in advance and supplementary duty paid on the inputs/raw materials declared by the Government in official gazette as non-refundable.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">The drawback facility is provided to exporters and deemed exporters of goods and services who import inputs or raw materials for the purpose of exportation only, after local value addition. But, only those who are not already enjoying bonded warehouse and cash incentive facilities are given this incentive.</span></p>', 0, '', 1464233029, '2016-05-26 03:23:49'),
(62, 1, 62, '<p>Yes.</p><p>The exporters, who also supply goods for home consumption within Bangladesh, can avail the duty drawback facility. But such drawback will be applicable only for the quantity of inputs that has gone into the finished goods they have exported, not for the inputs used in their total output.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">The exporters who operate businesses under Bonded Warehouse licenses and EPZ system, and the 100 per cent export-oriented and 100 per cent deemed exporters will be able to get drawbacks only for VAT paid on utilities consumed during the production of their export products.</span></p>', 0, '', 1464233045, '2016-05-26 03:24:05'),
(63, 1, 63, '<p>Duty drawback claims must be filed within six months of export (i.e. within six months of submitting the bill of export/export declaration), for both direct and deemed exporters.<br></p>', 0, '', 1464233105, '2016-05-26 03:25:05'),
(64, 1, 64, '<p>As per the Value Added Tax Act 1991, and section 39 of the Customs Act, 1969, in order to get duty drawback, diplomatic missions will have to apply within 6 months from the date of official purchase of locally produced goods, on which they have paid VAT. Purchases will have to be in local currencies only and must be made from a VAT registered firm/person. &nbsp;[Reference: NBR File No. 6(11) VAT-1/91/139 (13) date- 15/07/1993]<br></p>', 0, '', 1464233135, '2016-05-26 03:25:35'),
(65, 1, 65, '<p>A person can lodge an application with the Duty Drawback and Exemption (DEDO) office in the prescribed form, known as Musak-22. Following documents will have to be submitted along with the application:</p><ul><li>Bill of Export (certified by customs)</li><li>Invoice &amp; Packing list (Original copy signed by Customs)</li><li>Bill of Lading/AWB/Truck receipt (signed by the concerned bank)</li><li>Export examination report.&nbsp;</li><li>Undertaking in a non-judicial stamp (of Tk. 150).&nbsp;</li><li>Proceeds realization certificate (PRC) in support of receipt of foreign currency</li><li>Photocopy of export L/C (duly attested by lien bank)</li><li>Photocopy of EXP form (duty attested by concerned bank)</li><li>Photocopy of VAT registration (attested by the firm)</li></ul>', 0, '', 1464233166, '2016-05-26 03:26:06'),
(66, 1, 66, '<p>The list of products on which the exporters may claim duty drawback from the Duty Exemption and Drawback Office (DEDO) and on which duty drawback is generally allowed is provided in the following Table:</p><p><br></p><table class=\"table table-bordered\">\r\n<tbody><tr>\r\n    <th>Serial no</th>\r\n    <th>Name of goods/item</th>\r\n</tr><tr>\r\n    <td>1</td>\r\n    <td>Knitwear</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>2</td>\r\n    <td>Shopping bag</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>3</td>\r\n    <td>Fuel</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>4</td>\r\n    <td>Wood/Timber (processed)</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>5</td>\r\n    <td>Special textile</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>6</td>\r\n    <td>Lamp shed</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>7</td>\r\n    <td>Electricity</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>8</td>\r\n    <td>Jute products</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>9</td>\r\n    <td>High Speed Diesel (HSD)</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>10</td>\r\n    <td>Photo Inlay &amp; Backboard</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>11</td>\r\n    <td>Gas</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>12</td>\r\n    <td>Plastic goods</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>13</td>\r\n    <td>Spun pre-stressed concrete (SPC) poles</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>14</td>\r\n    <td>Insulator</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>15</td>\r\n    <td>Leather</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>16</td>\r\n    <td>Surgical goods</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>17</td>\r\n    <td>Power transformer</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>18</td>\r\n    <td>Metal zipper</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>19</td>\r\n    <td>MS products</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td>20</td>\r\n    <td>Urea</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n\r\n</tbody></table>', 0, '', 1464233775, '2016-05-26 03:36:15'),
(67, 1, 67, '<p>When duty drawback is given on the basis of actual rate, determination of input-output coefficient is necessary.&nbsp;</p><p>The Input-Output Co-efficient is not fixed and is subject to change.</p><p>However, in the case of drawback based on flat rate, this co-efficient is not necessary, because there is an NBR office order as to the amount of drawback to be given for each item on a flat rate basis.</p>', 0, '', 1464233804, '2016-05-26 03:36:44'),
(68, 1, 68, '<p>Yes. </p><p>In certain situations, one can. Subject to fulfillment of IPO conditions, one can import the following categories against LCA Form, but without letter of Credit (L/C), as per paragraph 8, sup-paragraph 3 of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018.</p><ol><li>Each consignment of quickly perishable food items worth US dollar Fifty Thousand via Teknaf Customs Station;</li><li>Each consignment of quickly perishable food items worth US Dollar Ten Thousand via other land customs stations; and</li><li>Essential food items irrespective of price limit via other land customs stations.</li></ol>', 0, '', 1464233894, '2016-05-26 03:38:14'),
(69, 1, 69, '<p>(A) Border haats are the market places constructed at the zero-point between India and Bangladesh at a number of designated areas. At the moment, several such border haats are in operation between the borders of Bangladesh with the Indian states of Meghalaya and Tripura. At these border haats, people from nearby areas can buy or sale products that are allowed through an agreement between the governments of Bangladesh and India.&nbsp;</p><p>(B) The size of each of the border haats will generally be 75?75 meters.</p><p>(C) On a single day, a person can purchase duty free goods up to a value equivalent to US$ 100 in local currency from the Border Haats.&nbsp;</p><p>Note: For updated information, please contact the FTA Wing under the Ministry of Commerce.</p>', 0, '', 1464233946, '2016-05-26 03:39:06'),
(70, 1, 70, '<p>Following products can be purchased duty and tax free from the Border Haats:</p><ol><li>Locally produced vegetables, food items, fruits and spices;</li><li>Locally made wooden items such as bamboo, bamboo grass, broom (except made of wood);</li><li>Locally made cottage industry items such as gamcha, lungi;</li><li>Locally made small-sized household agricultural equipment e.g. Cutlass, Plough, Axe, Spade, Chisel etc.; and</li><li>Locally manufactured RMG, Melamine products, processed food, fruit juice, toiletries, plastic products, aluminum products, crockeries etc.&nbsp;</li></ol><p>It is to be noted that locally manufactured or produced products/goods means goods/products produced/manufactured in Bangladesh or India.&nbsp;</p><p>Note: For updated information, please contact the FTA Wing under the Ministry of Commerce.</p>', 0, '', 1464233985, '2016-05-26 03:39:45'),
(71, 1, 71, '<p>(A) At present, Bangladesh has 181 Land Customs Stations along its border with India and Myanmar that can handle Bangladesh?s trade cargo with India and Myanmar.&nbsp;</p><p>(B) For the full list of importable and exportable goods through the Land Customs Stations, please see the Statutory Regulatory Order no. 114-Law/2013/2427/Cus, date 29 April 2013.&nbsp;</p>', 0, '', 1464234003, '2016-05-26 03:40:03'),
(72, 1, 72, '<p>In the case of export: All types of products are exportable through Benapole Custom House.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;In the case of import: All products, except two items, can be imported through Benapole Custom House. The two items that cannot be imported through Benapole Custom House include-</p><p>(a)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>Yarn (except yarn imported under bonded warehouse facility by 100% export-oriented knit garment industries); and&nbsp;</p><p>(b)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>Milk powder.&nbsp;</p><p>[Ref: SRO 114-Law/2013/2427/Cus, dated 29 April, 2013]</p>', 0, '', 1464234017, '2016-05-26 03:40:17'),
(73, 1, 73, '<p>In the case of export: All types of products are exportable through Sona Mosjid Land Customs Station.</p><p>In the case of import: All products, except the following items, can be imported through Sona Mosjid Land Customs Station. The items that cannot be imported through Sona Mosjid LC Station include-</p><p>(a)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>All types of paper and paperboard, including Duplex board, Newsprint, Craft paper, and Cigarette paper;</p><p>(b)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>Yarn;</p><p>(c)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>Milk powder;&nbsp;</p><p>(d)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>Juice; and</p><p>(e)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>Tobacco (except tobacco stem imported by established VAT-registered Bidi manufacturing industries).</p>', 0, '', 1464234038, '2016-05-26 03:40:38'),
(74, 1, 74, '<p>In the case of export: All types of products are exportable through Teknaf Land Customs Station.</p><p>In the case of import: All products, except the following items, can be imported through Teknaf Land Customs Station. The items that cannot be imported through Teknaf LC Station include-</p><p>(a)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>Yarn;</p><p>(b)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>Milk powder;&nbsp;</p><p>(c)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>Sugar; and</p><p>(d)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>Potato (except HS Code 0701.90.19 and 0701.90.29).</p>', 0, '', 1464234072, '2016-05-26 03:41:12'),
(75, 1, 75, '<p>In the case of export: All types of products are exportable through Chhatok Land Customs Station.</p><p>In the case of import: Only the following classes of products, except fish, yarn, milk powder, sugar and potato (other than HS Code 0701.90.19 and 0701.90.29), can be imported through Chhatok LC Station:</p><p>(a)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>Livestock, fish fry, fresh fruits, plants, seeds, wheat, stones and boulder, coal, chemical fertilizer, china clay, timber, limestone, onions, chilies, ginger, ball clay, quartz; and&nbsp;</p><p>(b)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>Only those products that have been imported fulfilling the procedures and conditions laid down in the SRO no. 255-Law/2002/1973/Cus, dated 19 September 2002, and with a certificate bearing quality, quantity, value and tariff classification of the goods.</p>', 0, '', 1464234084, '2016-05-26 03:41:24'),
(76, 1, 76, '<p>The Customs Act, 1969 imposes customs duty on goods imported into or exported from Bangladesh (section 18). This import duty and export duty are known as tariffs. The First Schedule of the Act contains statutory rates of import duty and export duty.<br></p>', 0, '', 1464234146, '2016-05-26 03:42:26'),
(77, 1, 77, '<p>A number of steps are involved in the process of Tariff Classification of a particular product/goods. These include-&nbsp;</p><p><b>(i) Identifying the Goods</b></p><p>The first step is to identify the goods in their imported condition. It is basically an objective and informed appraisal of what are the distinguishing characteristics of the goods.</p><p><b>(ii) Identifying Relevant Chapter for the Goods&nbsp;</b></p><p>Once the goods have been identified, the process of tariff classification involves checking at various chapters of the First Schedule of the Customs Act, 1969, and identify the relevant chapter for this particular goods.&nbsp;</p><p>These range from:&nbsp;</p><ul><li>animals and animal products (Chapters 1-5)</li><li>vegetable products (Chapters 6-14)</li><li>animal or vegetable fats and oils (Chapter 15)</li><li>prepared foodstuffs; beverages, spirits &amp; vinegar; tobacco &amp; manufactured substitutes (Chapters 16-24)</li><li>mineral products (Chapters 25-27)</li><li>products of chemical and allied industries (Chapters 28-38)</li><li>plastics and rubber articles (Chapters 39-40)</li><li>hides; skins; saddlery; travel goods, handbags (Chapters 41-43)</li><li>wood, charcoal, cork, manufactured straw (Chapters 44-46)</li><li>wood pulp or fibrous material; paper/paperboard (Chapters 47-49)</li><li>textiles and textile articles (Chapters 50-63)</li><li>footwear; headgear; umbrellas; feathers/down; artificial flowers, wigs (Chapters 64-67)</li><li>stone, plaster, cement, asbestos, mica, ceramics, glass and glassware (Chapters 68-70)</li><li>semi-precious/precious stones; &nbsp;pearls; &nbsp;imitation jewellery; &nbsp;coins (Chapter 71)</li><li>base metals and base metal articles (Chapters 72-83)</li><li>machinery &amp; mechanical appliances; electrical equipment; sound recorders/reproducers; televisions (Chapters 84-85)</li><li>vehicles; aircraft; vessels; associated equipment (Chapters 86-89)</li><li>optical, photographic, cinematographic equipment; medical/surgical instruments or apparatus; clocks/watches; musical instruments (Chapters 90-92)</li><li>arms and ammunition (Chapter 93)</li><li>miscellaneous manufactured articles (Chapters 94-96)</li><li>works of art; collectors? pieces and antiques (Chapter 97).</li></ul><p><b>(iii) Using ?General Rules for the Interpretation? of HS System</b></p><p>After identifying the relevant chapter, Customs seek guidance from the General Rules for Interpretation of the Harmonized Commodity Description and Coding System to identify the relevant Rule for selecting the appropriate HS Code of the product. When applying the Rules, if &nbsp;more clarification is required regarding the appropriateness of the selected Chapter or Heading or Sub-heading for the Goods, Customs consult the relevant Section Notes, Chapter Notes, Heading Notes and Sub-heading Notes of &nbsp;the Harmonized System Explanatory Notes.</p><p>Please note that under Rule 1 of the General Rules for the Interpretation, titles of Sections, Chapters and Sub-chapters are provided for ease of reference only. But, for legal purposes, classification shall, first and foremost, be determined according the terms of the headings and any relative Section or Chapter Notes, unless Rule 1 proves to be inconclusive for determining the classification of the particular goods, and use of subsequent Rule(s) becomes necessary. &nbsp;</p><p><b>(iv) Determining Tariff Classification Code</b></p><p>Once the relevant Chapter or Heading or Sub-heading is identified, the final step involves determination of the appropriate eight digit HS Code (varyingly called the National Tariff Line) and the associated customs duty in the First Schedule of the Customs Act.</p>', 0, '', 1464234234, '2016-05-26 03:43:54'),
(78, 1, 78, '<p>Windshield glass or safety glass to be used in motor vehicles are to be classified under HS Code 7007.11.00 or 7007.21.00 depending on their features. Similarly, rear view mirrors for vehicles will be classifiable under HS Code 7009.10.00.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">As per Rule 3(a) of the General Rules for Interpretation of the Harmonized System, a more complete or precise description will be preferred over the more general description. As Heading 70.07 (windshield or safety glass) or 70.09 (rear view mirror) provides the most specific description of these classes, &nbsp;headings 70.07 or 70.09 shall be preferred to heading 87.08 that provides a more general description of all motor parts. Therefore, Heading 87.08 (motor parts) will not be applicable for windshield glass or safety glass or rear view mirror, even though they can be considered as motor parts in some ways.</span></p>', 0, '', 1464234256, '2016-05-26 03:44:16'),
(79, 1, 79, '<p>No.</p><p>As the WCO is an intergovernmental organization, such questions should be brought to the attention of the national Customs administration concerned, which might then ask the WCO Secretariat to place the issue on the agenda of the Harmonized System Committee. Once the decision of the WCO is communicated to the member Customs Administration (e.g. Bangladesh), the trader can obtain the ruling/decision from that Administration (e.g. NBR/Customs).</p>', 0, '', 1464234270, '2016-05-26 03:44:30'),
(80, 1, 80, '<p>There are two main steps in determining Customs duty and other taxes. These are- :</p><ol><li>Determining the tariff classification: Customs first ascertain the appropriate tariff classification, which is known as the HS Code (Harmonized System Code) after consulting Bangladesh Customs Tariff in conjunction with the WCO Harmonized Commodity Description and Coding System. Once the appropriate HS Code is determined, the applicable Customs duty rate is applied based on Bangladesh Customs Tariff or the 1st Schedule of the Customs Act, 1969.&nbsp;<span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">In applying the appropriate duty rate, the issue of duty exemptions/preferential tariff, if any, is also taken into consideration.</span></li><li><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Determining the value for assessment purposes: Under section 25 of the Customs Act, 1969, the basis for determination of value for assessment purposes is the price actually paid or payable (in other words, the transaction value). The valuation principles, applicable for this purpose, are laid down under the Customs Valuation (Determination of Value of Imported Goods) Rules, 2000.</span></li></ol>', 0, '', 1464234313, '2016-05-26 03:45:13'),
(81, 1, 81, '<p><b>(A) Assessable value for Customs duty</b> = Assessable value of goods for the purpose of assessing the amount of Customs Duty is calculated in the following way:</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\"><b>First, the CIF Value is determined</b> = Cost (price actually paid or payable)+ Freight (if not known, 20% of FOB value) + Insurance cost (if actual insurance cost is not known, it is 1% of C&amp; F value)</span><br></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Then landing charge is added with the CIF value. Landing charge is assessed as 1% of CIF value</span></p><p><b>Example</b>: For a certain import, let C&amp;F cost = Tk. 100</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Therefore,&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Insurance cost = Tk. 1 (1% of C&amp;F) or actual&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; CIF cost = Tk. 101 (C&amp;F + Insurance)</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Landing charge = Tk. 1.01 (1% of CIF)&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Assessable value = Tk. 102.01 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Now, if the Customs Duty rate is 10%, then Customs Duty will be 10% of Tk. 102.01, which is Tk. 10.20</p><p><b>(B) Supplementary Duty (SD)</b>: Like VAT, Supplementary Duty (SD) is calculated on a cumulative basis. In other words, SD is computed on the duty paid value.&nbsp;</p><p>Therefore, the basis for calculation of SD will be: Assessable value + Customs Duty + Regulatory Duty (if any). &nbsp;</p><p>Example: &nbsp;if SD rate is 25%, the basis for calculation of SD in the previous example will be as follows:</p><p>102.01 (Assessable value) + 10.20 (Customs Duty at the rate of 10% flat rate) + 4.08 (Regulatory Duty at the rate of 4% flat rate) = Tk. 116.29</p><p>The computed value of SD will be: 116.29 * 25% = Tk. 29.0725</p>', 0, '', 1464234408, '2016-05-26 03:46:48'),
(82, 1, 82, '<p>In Bangladesh, there are only four products/items on which export duty is currently applicable. These include-&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Rice bran (HS Code 2302.40.10): Applicable export duty rate is 10%.</li><li>Unmanufactured tobacco; Tobacco refuse (HS Heading 24.01): &nbsp;Applicable export duty rate is 10%.</li><li>Cotton waste (HS Code 5202.99.10): Applicable export duty rate is 25%.&nbsp;</li><li>Building bricks (HS Code 6904.10.00): Applicable export duty rate is 25%.</li></ul>', 0, '', 1464234483, '2016-05-26 03:48:03'),
(83, 1, 83, '<p>No.&nbsp;</p><p>The valuation principles for old/used/reconditioned motor cars are laid down in the Statutory Regulatory Order (SRO) no 149-Law/2013/2436/Cus, dated 06/07/2013. In the determination of value, issues such as the cylinder capacity, the year of manufacturing, model code, chassis no. etc. also play important role.&nbsp;</p><p>In the case of import of old/used/reconditioned motor cars and vehicles, the value for customs purposes will be calculated on the following bases:</p><p>(a)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>If imported from Japan, the value will be the average value based on all code models of vehicles in the updated Yellow Book published in Japan;</p><p>(b)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>If imported from any country other than Japan, the value will be the average value based on all code models of vehicles published in the updated Glass?s Guide, Magazine Automobiles or internationally recognized journals of similar nature.&nbsp;</p><p>However, if your declared value exceeds the value from the above references, it will then be accepted for the assessment purpose.&nbsp;</p>', 0, '', 1464234506, '2016-05-26 03:48:26'),
(84, 1, 84, '<p>Yes.&nbsp;</p><p>The provision regarding this issue is delineated under the NBR office order no. 7(12)Cus-1/94/502, dated 23 August 2005.&nbsp;</p><p>According to this provision, when machinery/spare parts are re-imported after conducting repair works abroad, duty will have to be paid.&nbsp;</p><p>In the case of normal import, for ascertaining the assessable value for that duty, the C&amp;F Value will be calculated taking only the followings into consideration:</p><p>(a)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>The ?inward freight charge? for re-importation; and&nbsp;</p><p>(b)<span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>Cost of repair works.&nbsp;</p><p>But in the case of passenger baggage, if that machinery/spare part is carried as an accompanied baggage and remains within the baggage weight-entitlement of the passenger, no freight charge will be applicable.</p>', 0, '', 1464234527, '2016-05-26 03:48:47'),
(85, 1, 85, '<p>If the imported food item is found not fit for human consumption or its edible life or shelf life is expired, Customs will not release the goods, and instead will adopt appropriate procedures aiming to dispose of the consignment through the adoption of standard destruction and disposal procedure.<br></p>', 0, '', 1464234569, '2016-05-26 03:49:29'),
(86, 1, 86, '<p>If on test of sample(s) of the consignment by the Bangladesh Atomic Energy Commission, it is found that the consignment contains radioactivity level above the acceptable limit, the consignment will not be released, and the concerned exporter/supplier will be bound to take it back at his own expense.&nbsp;</p><p>[Reference: Paragraph 16 (6) of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018]</p>', 0, '', 1464234579, '2016-05-26 03:49:39'),
(87, 1, 87, '<p>Provisions in this regard are laid down in Section 82(1) of the Customs Act, 1969.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">In the case of goods unloaded in a customs port or a land customs station or customs inland container depot, they may be kept for 30 days (from the date of unloading). In the case of goods unloaded at a customs airport, they may stay for 21 days (from the date of unloading). This period, however, may be extended by the appropriate officer.&nbsp;</span><br></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">If goods are not cleared after that period, they may be sold after issuing a notice to the owner.&nbsp;</span><br></p>', 0, '', 1464234596, '2016-05-26 03:49:56'),
(88, 1, 88, '<p>Provisions in this regard are laid down in Section 82(1) of the Customs Act, 1969.</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">In the case of goods at a sea port, customs port or a land customs station or customs inland container depot, goods may be sold through auction after 30 days from the date of unloading or after an extended period (if extended by the appropriate officer). For goods at a Customs airport, goods become liable for auction, if not cleared within 21 days from the date of unloading or after an extended period.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">Due notice will have to be given to the owner before selling goods through auction.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">However, this above time table will not be applicable in the following cases:&nbsp;</span><br></p><p>(a) Animals and perishable and hazardous goods may, with the permission of the appropriate officer, be sold at any time;</p><p>(b) Arms, ammunition or military stores may be sold or otherwise disposed of at such time and place and in such manner as the Government may direct.</p>', 0, '', 1464234622, '2016-05-26 03:50:22'),
(89, 1, 89, '<p>Import prohibited goods, in particular old vehicles/conveyance, old engines and spare parts and fabrics importable under certain conditions may be sold through auction subject to prior permission of the Ministry of Commerce, and observance of provisions/rules under the Customs Act.</p><p>[Reference: NBR nothi no. 4(25) Shulka-8/93 (part-1)/65-90, dated 28/03/2001]</p>', 0, '', 1464234641, '2016-05-26 03:50:41'),
(90, 1, 90, '<p>No.&nbsp;</p><p>An importer cannot take delivery of just any category of products he wishes from the off-dock facilities.&nbsp;</p><p>An off-dock facility is a bonded Customs facility located outside the confines of the port and is operated by private-sector concerns. The off-docks have been established to ease the congestion problem of the port, especially in Chittagong.</p><p>Customs has identified a list of products (at present it includes 36 categories of products) which can be transferred from the port area to the off-dock facility before customs clearance. An importer is allowed to take to the off-docks only those category of products. He can get clearance of delivery of only those products from the off-docks which are allowed to be taken to there.</p>', 0, '', 1464234696, '2016-05-26 03:51:36'),
(91, 1, 91, '<p>Customs has identified a number of items or category of products that can be taken to the off-docks or the private ICDs for completion of customs formalities there with a view to easing congestion at the Chittagong Port. The NBR has allowed the following items to be transferred to the private ICDs/off-docks through its letters dated 06/07/2006, 02/09/2010, 06/12/2012, and 21/04/2015)</p><ol><li>Rice</li><li>Wheat</li><li>Mustard seed</li><li>Waste paper</li><li>Chickpeas (chola)&nbsp;</li><li>Pulse (dal)</li><li>Raw cotton</li><li>Scrap</li><li>Animal fodder&nbsp;</li><li>Hard coke&nbsp;</li><li>Carbon black</li><li>Marble chips</li><li>Ball clay (in bulk)</li><li>Onion</li><li>Ginger</li><li>Garlic (perishable goods carried in normal dry container)</li><li>Fertiliser&nbsp;</li><li>Soda Ash&nbsp;</li><li>PVC Resin</li><li>Staple Fibre&nbsp;</li><li>Containerised square/round Log</li><li>Dates</li><li>Bitumin</li><li>Empty container for beverages&nbsp;</li><li>Marble stone</li><li>Sodium sulphate</li><li>Wood pulp</li><li>Global salt</li><li>Soyabean meal/Extraction (2304 00 00);&nbsp;</li><li>DDGS (2308.00.00); &nbsp;</li><li>Rice Bran (2302.40.00);&nbsp;</li><li>Corn Glutten Meal (2302.10.00);&nbsp;</li><li>Rape Seed Extraction &nbsp;(2306.49.00);&nbsp;</li><li>Palm Kernels (2306.60.00);&nbsp;</li><li>Maize (1005.90.90); and</li><li>Soyabean (1201.90.90) &nbsp;&nbsp;</li></ol>', 0, '', 1464234786, '2016-05-26 03:53:06'),
(92, 1, 92, '<p>(A) Various fees and charges imposed by Customs on or in connection with importation or exportation include ?&nbsp;</p><ol><li>Document processing fee (for automated Customs assessment): at the rate of BDT 30.00 per bill of entry.&nbsp;</li><li>PSI services charge (in case of goods imported under Pre-shipment Inspection System): It is imposed under Section 25C of the Customs Act, 1969. The rate for such charge is 1% of the value of goods. (After the abolition of mandatory PSI system, this charge has become redundant)</li><li>Merchant overtime charge or MOT charge (in case of overtime duties by Customs officials).</li><li>Container scanning charge: at the rate US$3.00 per FCL container, and at the rate of US$1.50 per LCL container.</li><li>Transshipment fees: It is imposed under Section 125 of the Customs Act, 1969.&nbsp;</li><li>Fees for supplying copy of document: &nbsp;It is imposed under Section 204 of the Customs Act, 1969.</li><li>Fees for supplying Customs information: It is imposed under Section 204A of the Customs Act, 1969.</li><li>Fees for amendment of documents: It is imposed under Section 205 of the Customs Act, 1969.</li><li>Fees for amendment of errors, etc.: It is imposed under Section 206 of the Customs Act, 1969.</li></ol><p>(B) Customs fees and charges are generally determined in order to recover costs incurred from the services rendered and to cover other administrative expenses.</p>', 0, '', 1464234864, '2016-05-26 03:54:24'),
(93, 1, 93, '<p>It is not fixed yet. The National Board of Revenue is currently working on developing the Advance Ruling system in Bangladesh, as part of its customs modernization program.&nbsp;</p><p>Once the advance ruling system is developed and implemented in Bangladesh, the NBR will be able to share information on this issue.&nbsp;</p>', 0, '', 1464234876, '2016-05-26 03:54:36'),
(94, 1, 94, '<p><span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">All firearms classifiable under HS Headings 93.02, 93.03, 93.04 and 93.05, including revolvers and pistols, are importable by the authorized dealers of firearms subject to prior permission of the Ministry of Home Affairs.</span><br></p><p>Such firearms are also importable by the Trading Corporation of Bangladesh or by persons on approval of the Ministry of Commerce with NOC/recommendation from the Ministry of Home Affairs.</p><p>But import of Air Guns is prohibited. Air Guns can only be imported for the use of Sports and Shooting Club subject to prior permission of the Ministry of Home Affairs.</p><p>(Reference: Annexure 1 of the Import Policy Order)</p><p>Note: For more information, please contact Ministry of Commerce.</p>', 0, '', 1464234908, '2016-05-26 03:55:08'),
(95, 1, 95, '<p>In the case of import of potato seeds and rice seeds, the requirements are laid down in paragraph 26(30) and 26(31) of the Import Policy Order. The importer will be required to submit, along with other import documents, a quarantine certificate issued by the original supplier and a phytosanitary certificate from the relevant government authority in the exporting country.&nbsp;</p><p>Again, in the case of potato seeds, a quarantine certificate will have to be obtained from the Plant Quarantine Department before clearing the imported potato seeds from the Customs Authority. In the case of import of hybrid rice seeds, the phytosanitary certificate must mention that the seed is purified with hot water treatment and with approved pesticides.&nbsp;</p><p>In both cases (potato seeds and rice seeds), an import permit issued by the Plant Quarantine Department must be submitted at the time of opening the L/C.</p><p>Note: For more details on these issues, please consult Import Policy Order, 2015-2018 or contact the Plant Quarantine Department under Ministry of Agriculture.</p>', 0, '', 1464234922, '2016-05-26 03:55:22'),
(96, 1, 96, '<p>As per paragraph 26(44) of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018, an importer must fulfil the following three conditions in order to import one day old chicks:</p><p>(i) A certificate issued by the authorized officer of the Department of Livestock of the exporting country, to the effect that the importable chicks are free from contagious disease must be submitted to Customs;</p><p>(ii) A certificate issued by the World Organization of Animal Health to the effect that the exporting country is free from Avian Influenza must be submitted to Customs; and</p><p>(iii) The importer must submit to the bank, at the time of opening the L/C, a certificate from the Director or an authorized officer of the Directorate of Livestock that he has either a hatchery or a breeder farm.</p><p>Note: For more information, please consult Import Policy Order, 2015-2018 or contact the Ministry of Fisheries and Livestock.</p>', 0, '', 1464234942, '2016-05-26 03:55:42'),
(97, 1, 97, '<p>As per provisions under paragraph 24(4) of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018, only the foreign exchange earning hotels can import beer and wine of all categories (HS Heading 22.03 to 22.06). In special cases, such items may be imported with approval of the Ministry of Commerce and prior permission from CCI&amp;E. However, in all cases of import of beers and alcoholic drinks, importers must first obtain license/permission from the Department of Narcotics Control.&nbsp;</p><p>Note: For more details, please consult Import Policy Order, 2015-2018 or contact the Department of Narcotics Control.</p>', 0, '', 1464234956, '2016-05-26 03:55:56'),
(98, 1, 98, '<p>As per paragraph 24(9)(f)( of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018, the minimum value addition requirements for RMG industry that import raw materials on ?no cost basis? are as follows:</p><p><br></p><table class=\"table table-bordered\">\r\n    <tbody><tr>\r\n        <th></th>\r\n        <th></th>\r\n        <th>Minimum value addition</th>\r\n    </tr>\r\n    <tr>\r\n        <td>1</td>\r\n        <td>Export of knit garments</td>\r\n        <td>20%</td>\r\n    </tr>\r\n    <tr>\r\n        <td>2</td>\r\n        <td>Export of non-quota category woven garments</td>\r\n        <td>20%</td>\r\n    </tr>\r\n    <tr>\r\n        <td>3</td>\r\n        <td>Export of quota category woven garments  up to a value of U/S$40 F.O.B. per dozen</td>\r\n        <td>20%</td>\r\n    </tr>\r\n    <tr>\r\n        <td>4</td>\r\n        <td>Export of quota category woven garments above the value of US$40  F.O.B. per dozen</td>\r\n        <td>20%<br>However, in no case, the value addition per dozen shall not be less than US$12.</td>\r\n    </tr>  \r\n    <tr>\r\n        <td>5</td>\r\n        <td>In the case of exports of higher priced garments</td>\r\n        <td>Value addition shall not be less than 15% and 10% for quota category and non-quota category respectively. \r\nHowever, in this case, the FOB value of each dozen shall be US $60 F.O.B. or more.</td>\r\n    </tr>  \r\n    <tr>\r\n        <td>6</td>\r\n        <td>Exports of all types of sweaters</td>\r\n        <td>20%</td>\r\n    </tr>  \r\n    <tr>\r\n        <td>7</td>\r\n        <td>Exports of all types of baby garments</td>\r\n        <td>15%</td>\r\n    </tr>  \r\n</tbody></table>\r\n<p>Note: For more information, please contact the Ministry of Commerce.</p>', 0, '', 1464235337, '2016-05-26 04:02:17'),
(99, 1, 99, '<p>Bangladesh Government controls the import of certain goods into Bangladesh. Such government controls are mainly of two types. These are-</p><ul><li>Restriction: There is a restriction or control list at Part (A) of Annexure 1 of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018. In addition to describing the products that are under the control list, Part (A) of Annexure 1 also elaborates on the conditionalities that need to be fulfilled if any product, categorized in the list according to Harmonized System (HS) Chapters and H.S. Codes, is to be imported.</li><li>Prohibition: Goods whose import are not allowed at any circumstances. These are of two categories. First, under section 15 of the Customs Act, 1969, import of a number of products into Bangladesh is prohibited. Secondly, import of more products are prohibited under Part (B) of Annexure 1 of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018.</li></ul><p>Note: For detailed information on restricted and prohibited items under the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018, please contact the Ministry of Commerce.</p>', 0, '', 1464235503, '2016-05-26 04:05:03'),
(100, 1, 100, '<p>Yes.</p><p>As per paragraph 24(12) of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018, recognized units under specialized textile industry operating under the bonded warehouse system are permitted to import raw and packing materials (including banned/restricted items) as determined by the customs authority on the basis of confirmed and irrevocable letter of credit for export of the items of specialized textile against back to back L/C.&nbsp;</p><p>For this purpose no prior permission from the Chief Controller is required.</p><p>Note: For more information, please contact the Ministry of Commerce.&nbsp;</p>', 0, '', 1464235519, '2016-05-26 04:05:19'),
(101, 1, 101, '<p>As per the provision under paragraph 26(2) of the Import Policy Order, 2015-2018, commercial import of explosive substances are not allowed except through the Trading Corporation of Bangladesh (TCB).<br></p>', 0, '', 1464235529, '2016-05-26 04:05:29'),
(102, 1, 102, '<p>A non-Resident (expatriate) Bangladeshi with income earned abroad, and any foreign investor with his share of equity can send or ship capital machinery &amp; raw materials/spare parts on CIF or CIP basis.&nbsp;</p><p>[Paragraph 5(5) of the Import Policy Order, 2015-18]</p>', 0, '', 1464235542, '2016-05-26 04:05:42'),
(103, 1, 103, '<p>List of Export -Prohibited Products:</p><ol><li>Soya bean oil, Palm oil</li><li>(a) All petroleum and petroleum products except those produced from natural gas (such as naphtha, furnace oil, lubricant oil, bitumen, condensate, MTT and MS). However, this prohibition shall not apply to the export of petroleum and LNG as shares of the foreign investment companies under the Product Sharing Contracts;&nbsp;<span style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">(b) Any passenger going abroad shall be allowed to carry goods as accompanied baggage, in excess of his or her personal goods, worth US$ 200, which are neither export -prohibited nor included in the list of conditional exports. In this case, no facilities/incentives like duty draw back adjustment, subsidy etc. shall be awarded;</span></li><li>Jute and `Shan? seeds;</li><li>Wheat;&nbsp;</li><li>Rice (except rice export at government-to-government level and aromatic rice);</li><li>All kinds of live animals, animal organs or hide/ skin of wild animals as mentioned in the Wildlife (Protection) Ordinance 1973 (President?s Ordinance No. 23, 1973, Revised in 1974), except the species mentioned in the first list of the Ordinance;</li><li>Fire arms, ammunition and related materials;</li><li>Radioactive materials;</li><li>Archeological relics, Human skeleton, blood plasma, or anything produced from human beings or human blood;</li><li>Human skeleton, blood plasma, or anything produced from human beings or human blood;</li><li>All types of pulses (except processed pulses);</li><li>All shrimps except chilled, frozen and processed ones;</li><li>Onion, garlic and ginger;</li><li>Seawater shrimps of 71/90 count or smaller, except the species harina and Chaka including sea species PUD, Cooked shrimp;</li><li>Cane wood, wood logs/ thick pieces of wood (except handicrafts made from these materials). However, rubber wood from Forest Industries Corporation may be exported to export processing zones as inputs for furniture industry, and will be treated as deemed exports;</li><li>All types of frogs (alive or dead) and frog legs;</li><li>Raw and wet blue leather.</li></ol><p>[Source: Annex-1 of Export Policy 2015-18]</p>', 0, '', 1464235662, '2016-05-26 04:07:42'),
(104, 1, 104, '<p>Urea fertilizer produced in all factories except KAFCO can be exported with the prior approval of the Ministry of Industries.&nbsp;</p><p>[Ref: Annex 2 of Export Policy 2015-18 (9.1 of List of Products under Conditional Export]</p><p>Note: For more information, please contact the Ministry of Industries.</p>', 0, '', 1464235678, '2016-05-26 04:07:58');
